\section{Duplicate rows}{

Some workbooks contain duplicate \verb{(Equ, CropIDx, Coef)} keys, from a do-file
that hardcoded \verb{mat roweq A = Female} inside the loop over treatment dummies:
those rows land on the \code{means} sheet tagged \code{Equ == "Female"} and collide with
the real \code{Female} outcome rows. Check for it in any workbook you read here.
\code{exhibit_value()} errors on duplicates rather than silently returning the
first match, which is what makes the collision visible at all.
}

\section{Sheet naming across studies}{

Sheet names are \strong{not} consistent, because each study's do-file names them
from its own treatment loop:

\tabular{lll}{
\strong{Study} \tab \strong{Engine A sheet(s)} \tab \strong{Engine B sheet} \cr
land_tenure \tab \code{means} (one treatment) \tab \code{land_tenure} \cr
resource_extraction \tab \code{Means_extraction_any}, \code{Means_mining_any},
\code{Means_mining_comm}, \code{Means_mining_gala}, \code{Means_quarrying},
\code{Means_sand}, \code{Means_salt} \tab \code{extraction}
}

\code{layout = "auto"} therefore does \strong{not} key off the sheet name. It inspects
the first three column headers as written by Stata (\verb{CropIDx, Equ, Coef} for
Engine A; \verb{Variable, crop, mesure} for Engine B) and picks accordingly. Keying
off the name would silently apply the wrong column names to
\code{Means_extraction_any}.
}

